        "description": "**Getting Started with Code.org:** Consider watching our [Getting Started with Code.org](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLzdnOPI1iJNdX7P76yGw7YUM4Csm1ZZmM) video series for an overview of how to navigate lesson plans, setup a classroom section, and other important features of the Code.org platform. Each video also has a support article if you'd prefer to read or print instructions - [click here to learn more](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/4405629586957-New-how-to-walkthrough-videos-for-teachers-).\n\n**Setup a Classroom Section:** You can use a class section in Code.org to manage your students, view their progress, and assign specific curriculum - [click here to learn more](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/115000488132-Creating-a-classroom-section).\n\nIf you are using a learning management system, there may be additional steps to sync your classes with Code.org:\n\n- [Click here](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/115001319312-Setting-up-sections-with-Google-Classroom-sync) for steps to setup your classes with Google Classroom\n- [Click Here](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/115002716111-Setting-up-sections-with-Clever-sync) for steps to setup your classes with Clever\n\n**Become a Verified Teacher:** Lesson plans and levels have additional resources and answer keys for Verified Teachers, which is quick process that verifies your position at an educational institution. [Click here to complete a form](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdGGAJuaDMBVIRYnimPhAL96w6fCl4UdvhwmynGONM75TWwWw/viewform) and you should have access to verified teacher resources in ~1 business day. Verified teachers also have access to the [\"Teacher's Lounge\"](https://forum.code.org/c/csd/csd-teachers-lounge/444) section of the forums.\n\n**Get Inspired:** Consider watching our [Teacher Tips video playlist](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLzdnOPI1iJNcc7Q-PvUVqV249l2JzhJes), featuring current CS Discoveries teachers.\n\n**Technical Requirements:** For the very best experience with all Code.org content, we recommend consulting with your school or district's IT department to _ensure specific sites **are allowed** and **are not blocked**_. **[Click here to see a list of sites to unblock](https://code.org/educate/it)**. \n\nYou can also find mobile and tablet support details, hardware recommendation information such as minimum Internet connection speed, smallest screen size supported, and other hardware recommendations, as well as a list of supported browsers and platforms at the same [technical requirements website](https://code.org/educate/it). ",
        "name": "Preparing for the Unit"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd4750e2-99f4-4964-ac72-c43f3c5ce265",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b960295-a1f2-48be-9d91-4023a6edb6d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9bd4d7e1-74d2-4f5c-b20f-1fbfe46ac669",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Get started with our new Self-Paced Professional Learning to explore the curriculum and Music Lab! Feel confident and prepared as you start teaching the unit! [**Click here to start learning!**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/1/levels/1)",
        "name": "Professional Learning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9bd4d7e1-74d2-4f5c-b20f-1fbfe46ac669",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b960295-a1f2-48be-9d91-4023a6edb6d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36139b20-e0c0-43b7-939b-41da7837c6c5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before starting this lesson, provide students with an opportunity to take the pre-assessment for the unit. You can decide to spend 10-15 minutes at the start of class completing this, or at the end of a previous class period. To ensure that students only take the pre-assessment at the appropriate time, it is \"locked\" and unviewable by them until you \"unlock\" it. The [How to Administer a Locked Survey or Assessment](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/115001331951-Using-lock-settings-for-assessments-and-surveys) document provides details on how to do that when you are ready.\n\nThe **pre-assessment** is a 10-question assessment covering topics students will learn in the unit. **Students will likely be unprepared for these questions** - that's what makes it a pre-assessment! Encourage students to try their best, but they will likely not know many of the answers. Let them know they will see similar questions at the end of the unit and can compare their scores to see how much they've learned! ",
        "name": "Pre-Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36139b20-e0c0-43b7-939b-41da7837c6c5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b960295-a1f2-48be-9d91-4023a6edb6d1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4665d84a-7c01-4d9a-b5fd-f5abf3dbf40a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Two Warm-Up Options:** This lesson has two warm-up options, depending on whether or not students have been previously introduced to the Problem Solving Process.\n\n**Option 1** is for classrooms that have not been introduced to the Problem Solving Process. The warm up is longer than normal because it introduces the Problem Solving Process through a brief activity and a video.\n\n**Option 2** is for classrooms that have been introduced to the Problem Solving Process in a previous unit. The warm-up is shorter and acts as a quick review of the Problem Solving Process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4665d84a-7c01-4d9a-b5fd-f5abf3dbf40a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "97962dd0-cf47-4760-ab1f-19f66e01f082",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this unit, we'll take on the role of music experience designers to help clients with their design problem. The word \"problem\" can refer to lots of different situations - I could say I have a problem for homework, a problem with my brother, and a problem with my car, and all three mean very different things.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Problem Solving Word Search",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "97962dd0-cf47-4760-ab1f-19f66e01f082",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81ac5005-35cb-4c10-9169-e6c0620c455a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Prompt:**  What's an example of a problem you've had to solve recently?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81ac5005-35cb-4c10-9169-e6c0620c455a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7f963a1c-c283-4e61-bb04-04891e4f5cb0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate & Distribute:** Have students share their thoughts with a neighbor. Listen for examples that may be worth using as examples throughout the lesson. \n\nAs students share, distribute a copy of the [Word Search](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1M1_eMuqtPX4Yo2eQl3JOo9MbSyPB-4C1mLYyNlh1HKc/view) to each student, face down. Make sure students don't start the word search ahead of time.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7f963a1c-c283-4e61-bb04-04891e4f5cb0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd59c8f8-3c35-4657-a5ae-ca70444c2d8b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Since we will most likely be faced with some problems to solve in this unit, today, we are going to learn about and practice an effective strategy for when we need to solve problems. We'll start with a simple problem: solving a word search.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd59c8f8-3c35-4657-a5ae-ca70444c2d8b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e55195c-0b25-45c8-8b34-9ee54bbb5d44",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** What is the problem you are trying to solve when you do a word search?\n\n**Discuss:** Allow students to discuss their ideas with a classmate before sharing them with the entire class.\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Guide students to the idea that the problem of a word search is that there are hidden words throughout the grid of letters and thus the goal of a word search is to find all the words in the list.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** What are the different strategies that someone could use for finding words? What are the pros and cons of each strategy?\n\n**Discuss:** Allow students to silently record their ideas in writing for a minute. Afterward, invite them to share what they wrote with a neighbor and then finally bring the whole class together to develop a classwide list of strategies.\n\n**Discussion Goal:** This is a quick, low-stakes brainstorm that asks students to bring in their own experiences with word searches and identify strategies they may have used or could use. Student responses may vary but may include the following strategies:\n* Scan each row from left to right followed by scanning each column from top to bottom.\n* Check surrounding letters. Once you found the first letter or a key letter in a word you’re searching for, check the letters around it to see if you should keep going. For example, if you have a word with Q in it, if there’s no U next to it, then you need to keep searching.\n* Look for words that have less-common letters in them such as words with a Q, X, J, or Z\n* Look for words with letter pairs, such as double letters or QU\n* Look for more than one word at a time.\n* Turn the puzzle upside down\n\n**Do This:** Direct students to pick ONE strategy from the list that they want to try and put a “#1” next to it in their journals to indicate it was their first strategy used. Once they pick a strategy, direct students to use that strategy in their word search.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It is important to let the students know that if at any time the strategy they picked is not working, they should feel free to go back to the list of strategies and pick a different one, making sure to put a number next to the new strategy."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e55195c-0b25-45c8-8b34-9ee54bbb5d44",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8208d4a0-7525-4c29-a57b-b20f1ba83f7b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate:** Give students a few minutes to find as many words as possible. It is okay if they don’t find every word. You may bring everyone back together once everyone has found at least several of the words on the list.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** Display and have students reflect on each of the following prompts:\n* Were you successful in solving this word search problem? How do you know?\n* What strategy did you pick and how did it work for you?\n* Did anyone change strategies at any point … why or why not?\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As you lead this discussion, you may choose to do a quick raise of hand poll to find out who was successful, or on track to be successful if they didn’t get a chance to finish. Additionally, you can also instruct students to pick two of the questions to answer."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8208d4a0-7525-4c29-a57b-b20f1ba83f7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "df9fae62-811c-4c80-8bbb-5001bfae5ae4",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discussion Goal:** This discussion serves as a way to get students to reflect on how they did solving this problem and to give students a moment to recognize if they changed strategies and why or if they would solve a problem like this differently next time."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "df9fae62-811c-4c80-8bbb-5001bfae5ae4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a42492a-9237-416d-9857-a9334c2d5c72",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show students the [r the_problem_solving_process/programming-with-music-lab/2025] video in the slides.\n\n**Questions to Consider with Video:**\n* What are the 4 steps to the Problem-Solving Process?",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "The Problem Solving Process",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the **[Guide to Curriculum Videos](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1c2hF3CaTJacvwDy4y_9-m1jSkSPmK__F6pDPetXVvy4/view)**."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a42492a-9237-416d-9857-a9334c2d5c72",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8169131d-b76d-47b3-8c8b-c03e3151ccf1",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss and Display:** Briefly discuss with students what parts of the warm-up activity they felt fell into each step of the problem-solving process before displaying the example answers in the slides:\n* Define: when we put into our own words what the problem of a word search is and what the goal is\n* Prepare: the brainstorming of different strategies that could be used to solve a word search\n* Try: when we picked a strategy and tried to find the words\n* Reflect: when we reflected on how they did at the end",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a good point to remind students that the problem-solving process is a cycle and there should be times when they need to repeat steps. For example, if they went back to the list of strategies and picked a different one at any point when solving this problem, they were not only doing the “Reflect” step without realizing it but going back to the “Prepare” and “Try” steps again.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8169131d-b76d-47b3-8c8b-c03e3151ccf1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "741106ac-0825-4c09-aec7-7a6cfdbdf003",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we're familiar with the problem-solving process, let's explore how we can use it when designing music for clients. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "741106ac-0825-4c09-aec7-7a6cfdbdf003",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d6cbe750-30e5-4e75-a5ef-536a7df31323"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f69dc8f4-1e56-44ae-b470-5d03b308831f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Two Warm-Up Options:** This lesson has two warm-up options, depending on whether or not students have been previously introduced to the Problem-Solving Process.\n\nOption 2 is for classrooms that have been introduced to the Problem-Solving Process in a previous unit. The warm-up is shorter and acts as a quick review of the Problem-Solving Process"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f69dc8f4-1e56-44ae-b470-5d03b308831f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1334a2a3-fd62-416a-834a-5fe899d049ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c620ed80-741a-464a-b65c-39d9e5661c3c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this unit, we'll take on the role of music experience designers to help clients with their design problem. Today, we are going to remind ourselves about the Problem Solving Process and eventually we will apply it to the music we create.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Revisit The Problem Solving Process",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c620ed80-741a-464a-b65c-39d9e5661c3c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1334a2a3-fd62-416a-834a-5fe899d049ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bf16f1d4-a83b-4081-af8a-e5391c1915bf",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** What do you remember about the Problem-Solving Process?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Based on student responses, the teacher should lead students through a discussion about the four steps of the Problem-Solving Process and what they remember to be involved in each step.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** Based on what you know about the Problem-Solving Process, what do you think each step could look like when designing an song?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Even though students haven't designed music yet, guide students to imagine the steps involved from having the first inspiration for a song to having it created. Some ideas may include:\n* Define: Deciding what you want the mood of the song to be or who you want to make it for\n* Prepare: Listening to other songs and deciding what kinds of sounds, effects, and patterns you want to use or thinking about how the user might interact with the music.\n* Try: Creating a basic version of the song (even if it doesn’t have all of the features)\n* Reflect: Showing it to friends to get feedback and improving the song\n\nAs students finish discussing, transition to the main activity.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bf16f1d4-a83b-4081-af8a-e5391c1915bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1334a2a3-fd62-416a-834a-5fe899d049ad"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ce54403-aa5d-49ca-a3d9-2dbbe2a589bb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this unit, we’re going to learn how to create interactive songs using Music Lab, which starts with thinking about who we’re creating music for. Sometimes we make music based on our own interests or moods, but it’s also important to think about designing songs that other people will enjoy or connect with.\n\nEventually, we’ll apply the problem-solving process to help us actually code our musical ideas. But today, we’re going to focus on how to use the problem-solving process to design songs and musical experiences that meet the needs of both ourselves and others.",
        "name": "Recommending Song Ideas to Clients",
        "progression_name": "User Stories"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ce54403-aa5d-49ca-a3d9-2dbbe2a589bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "855801e7-1d85-4b77-8b43-794928e1c89e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Group:** Put students in pairs.\n\n**Distribute:** Pass out a copy of the [activity guide](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1YDGmbxZSHZhvMWVPzoawNm0ceKRoPffgt1kc0HQDWhk/view) to each student. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Answer Keys & Exemplars:** An answer key or exemplar is provided for verified teachers as part of the resources in this lesson plan. If you do not see an answer key or exemplar listed as a resource, [follow these steps](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/115001550131-Becoming-a-verified-teacher-CS-Principles-and-CS-Discoveries-only-) to become a verified teacher."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "855801e7-1d85-4b77-8b43-794928e1c89e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4a53c418-84d7-4e89-8339-b47d51256936",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Overview:** Have students read through the directions on the first page of the activity guide. The first part of this activity asks students to match different users to an song that suits their needs. Students will need to visit Code Studio to view the song prototypes.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Example Song Player:** This lesson is an opportunity for students to familiarize themselves with the \"Example Player\" embedded into levels. In these levels, this is the only way students can interact with each level. In future lessons, these examples provide guidance to students on how to complete their songs, so it's important students are familiar with this player!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4a53c418-84d7-4e89-8339-b47d51256936",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a10b8caa-602c-4c72-aefe-78bca090660e",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Client Stories"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a10b8caa-602c-4c72-aefe-78bca090660e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ecb4360b-6dc0-4434-a46f-c077ab9a8c4d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate:** Have students work through this activity in pairs, encouraging discussion about why exactly they are choosing each template. This is a great place to discuss different songdesigns and the needs of each client.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Value Reasoning over Correctness:** There are more than one answer for some of the clients. Students are encouraged to use their own reasoning and logic when recommending a prototype to their client. It's okay for students to not make an \"obvious\" choice as long as they're thinking carefully about their reasoning and are able to justify their choices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ecb4360b-6dc0-4434-a46f-c077ab9a8c4d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce0d0101-a987-4c6c-96a4-cb33e6322b59",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Share Out:** Have students discuss the following questions in small groups before bringing them to a full class discussion:\n* Which users were the easiest to find matches for?\n* Which users were the hardest to find matches for?\n\nBased on your observations while circulating, you should also identify a few specific users to ask the class to discuss, especially users for whom multiple students chose different templates for that user. Encourage students to hear different justifications for their choices, emphasizing that the rationale is more important than the choice itself.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "As students discuss their reasoning for their choices, check to ensure that they are identifying the particular client's needs and characteristics, rather than general reasons to prefer a song. You may want to challenge students to distinguish their own needs and preferences from those of the described client."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce0d0101-a987-4c6c-96a4-cb33e6322b59",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8ec2f593-6008-4a01-aae4-ea065dd0f628",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now we've been asked to design a song ourselves for a client. We can create our own design, but it should meet the needs of our users.",
        "name": "Designing a Song",
        "progression_name": "Prepare & Try",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Note on Timing:** Depending on how long the warm-up took, especially if the class watched the problem-solving video, you may run out of time to fully complete this activity. That's okay! It can be something students come back to as they progress throughout the unit, or you may decide to extend this activity into a new class period and stretch out the design and feedback process. This task can be implemented in a variety of ways to match the constraints of the classroom."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8ec2f593-6008-4a01-aae4-ea065dd0f628",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d047dbda-d6ef-46dc-9005-a1a579c9cde9",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Overview:** Have students flip to the back of their activity guide and read the overview of the next part of the activity. Students will choose a user to create a song design for, following the Problem-Solving Process. \n\n**Transition** Have students navigate to Lesson 1, Level 2. During the \"Prepare & Try\" section of their Activity Guide, they are asked to explore different sounds in the Code.org Sound Library. When they find a sound that meets their client's needs, they should write down the sound name on their Activity Guide. \n\n**Circulate:** Monitor students as they complete this activity, ensuring that students are creating designs that match the needs of the user they chose. Monitor student conversations as well to make sure both voices are being heard during discussions and decisions. Students will be working in pairs throughout the unit, so it can be good to intervene early to reinforce good collaboration habits.\n\n**(Optional) Share Out:** Depending on how much time is left in class, allow students to trade with other groups and share their song ideas. Encourage students to share with another group who picked the same user so they can see similarities and differences in their designs.\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Prepare & Try",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Exploring Different Sounds:** Music Lab provides a wide variety of custom sounds that students can integrate into songs. This level provides an explicit opportunity for students to explore this wide library of sounds in an open-ended way. Ideally, students \"get it all out of their system\" in this level and can then focus on solving problems in future lessons. So - really lean-in to letting students explore and identify sounds they like so it doesn't become a distraction in future lessons and projects!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d047dbda-d6ef-46dc-9005-a1a579c9cde9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0257d208-8267-4bc5-9c59-f90ba60e0400",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Following the Problem-Solving Process:** You can use student responses on the activity guide to determine how well they followed each step of the problem-solving process. This process will be reinforced throughout the unit, especially on projects."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0257d208-8267-4bc5-9c59-f90ba60e0400",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6a3152c6-07fc-42c6-8f31-ed194bd9f653"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9d7e7c5-bf94-438f-b5a0-047ef717133d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Prompt:** Reflect - What was one thing that you think your design does well to meet the needs of the user? What’s an area that you think can still be improved to meet the needs of your user?\n\n**Circulate:** Students can answer these prompts on their activity guide in the Reflect section of the Problem Solving Process.\n\n**Share Out:** Have students share their responses, highlighting similarities between responses even when the users were different.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9d7e7c5-bf94-438f-b5a0-047ef717133d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "52caaaa6-8fbc-4364-aed8-611ff14aa16c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ae608b8b-c4a9-4341-b696-27c305c216bf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The next set of lessons introduces **Sequencing** with brand new blocks and programming strategies. Feel prepared to teach these lessons by reviewing our Self-Paced Professional Learning specifically for these lessons - in under 30 minutes! [**Click here to start now!**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/2/levels/1)",
        "name": "Just-In-Time Professional Learning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ae608b8b-c4a9-4341-b696-27c305c216bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b70d8f9-5030-45fe-81ac-d3ac274f1832"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b8bbb493-ae62-4196-9706-dcc9e4ab99a6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the [Make Music, Learn Code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GqlP5s7KTl4) video\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Think Pair Share:** After watching the video, silently brainstorm how music and technology work together how using computers to make music creates new opportunities for musicians. Then have student turn to a partner to share. Call on 2-3 groups to share their discussion. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Use this prompt to surface observations from the video about how music and technology are interconnected, such as designing songs fully \"within the box\". Extend the discussion to highlight areas that students may be excited by as they learn more about music lab.\n\n**Distribute:** [Problem Solving & Computational Thinking](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1b670YBrm2H0PwBKAVoef7lfdsI3ci5SYJz9zWnWTiRI/template/preview) resource. Students will use this resource to follow a clear problem-solving process and apply computational thinking strategies at each step to solve complex problems effectively.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show students the four aspects of computational thinking:\n- **Algorithmic Thinking:** Going step-by-step to solve a problem\n- **Pattern Recognition:** Using similarities and patterns to solve a problem\n- **Abstraction:** Breaking down a problem into smaller pieces\n- **Decomposition:** Focusing on important details to solve a problem\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> There are many ways music and technology are connected in real-life, but another important aspect is how musicians and computer scientists think about creating songs or solving problems. Throughout this unit, we're going to explore four key computational mindsets for how to create songs with code. Be on the lookout for these as we learn more about Music Lab today!",
        "progression_name": "Make Music, Learn Code Video"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b8bbb493-ae62-4196-9706-dcc9e4ab99a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9789fe37-fa91-44fa-839c-fa1cf7a208f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fb59e116-bdd2-4486-9425-4b92c6ea14a4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students open the Explore level and read the instructions. Students are asked to complete a series of tasks to help them become familiar with navigating Music Lab. Give students time to explore and experiment on their own.",
        "progression_name": "Explore"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fb59e116-bdd2-4486-9425-4b92c6ea14a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c97e51c4-6f73-42db-b2ee-97938e967b22",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Regroup:** As a class, go through each of the tasks in the level. Ask students to explain how they solved certain tasks before explaining yourself. Be sure to highlight that students can click on the <i class=\"fa-solid fa-lightbulb\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-square-right\"></i> icons to see special callouts as hints within the level.\n\n[Click here to see a video of a curriculum team member exploring this level](https://www.loom.com/share/01b5fd8ef8f04002b09f61fbfdf6dc9a), highlighting each of the tasks in this level and additional features in music lab. You can decide how many of these features you would like to show to the whole class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c97e51c4-6f73-42db-b2ee-97938e967b22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "01c92c49-c9df-4201-96a0-270f3ffb4906",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Predict level. Have students respond to the two questions within the level:\n- Write down anything you **notice** about the code\n- Make a **prediction** - what do you think will happen when you press Run?\n\nOnce students have made a prediction, they can press Run to see the result.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**No Wrong Answers** - These questions are intentionally structured to encourage \"no wrong answer\" thinking, which invites students to make unstructured observations and participate in class discussions. These predict levels are based on the PRIMM pedagogy for teaching coding, which shows increased engagement and ownership when students are asked to form hypotheses about code before seeing it in action. As you structure these discussions, ensure all students feel supported in participating and try to avoid confirming or denying any ideas and instead letting students make those observations themselves when running the code.\n\n**Music Terminology**- A shared vocabulary is the foundation of meaningful collaboration. The third page of this [Anchor Chart set](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/12R4e0xxMFBbkyu4gaXbXfwyLba-OjivpRNggZlw8hiE/edit?usp=sharing) could be a powerful resource to share with students at this point. Additionally, the [Music Terms Glossary](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1wvllTFs0IBWJI8uzfUhuFW4mUYItUK5nmmVjArNRlCM/edit?usp=sharing) includes definitions and explanations to support instruction.  "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "01c92c49-c9df-4201-96a0-270f3ffb4906",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a0c499c2-5020-4ee3-997d-407e51f39958",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Predict"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a0c499c2-5020-4ee3-997d-407e51f39958",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "979e5212-f057-4ce6-8fcf-b75b8f363c97",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Once the class has seen the code, lead a discussion about what went as expected and what was surprising. Explicitly explain how the `play together` block works, and that since the Bass track is on the outside it will play afterwards. Ensure students understand why the code behaves the way it does before continuing. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "979e5212-f057-4ce6-8fcf-b75b8f363c97",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "61bb38e3-8a5a-4151-924b-04368f0c5163",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students should work through the Investigate levels independently or with a partner. This allows you to circulate and provide targeted support. Your goal is to check in with every student or pair, which is a high-impact practice for boosting engagement.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Viewing Example Solutions:** Each level has an example solution that verified teachers can access and view. You can view example solutions by expanding the Teacher Panel from the right-side of the screen, then clicking the blue \"Example Solution\" button. This process is [highlighted in this video](https://www.loom.com/share/36ee8c6709aa4e8dbe2449103e1b07be) and the graphic below\n\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/e2be70507c3a22a08d28a3cd7c8cdd5a-example-solutions.png\" style=\"width: 25%\">"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "61bb38e3-8a5a-4151-924b-04368f0c5163",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9aacf19f-96d2-47e0-b35d-25c31f23f823",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work independently, your presence and encouragement can have a powerful impact. A simple check-in can boost confidence, uncover misunderstandings, or spark deeper thinking. Use this time to:\n\n- Notice patterns then use this info to tailor your next move.\n- Ask open-ended questions to prompt reflection and reasoning.\n- Celebrate progress: Point out creative approaches or persistence, even if a solution isn't perfect yet.\n\nIf students are stuck, guide them to:\n- Re-read the step-by-step instructions and click the icons for hints\n- Listen to the example song for clues\n- Try one idea and observe what happens\n\n**<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i>  Do This (Optional):** Once enough students have completed the Investigate levels, consider regrouping to talk through the levels as a class. This is a good opportunity to cement student thinking on key concepts from the lesson while also elevating student voices by calling on students to help you complete levels in front of the class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9aacf19f-96d2-47e0-b35d-25c31f23f823",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d9455ee-e920-42df-b767-a90b66e2c136",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Check-In level. The remaining levels can be completed independently at students' own pace."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d9455ee-e920-42df-b767-a90b66e2c136",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0aa3f9b8-70d8-4e39-9c2a-6c436a17c2d0",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check-In",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels.\n- Use the tips and guiding questions on the [Sequencing Cheat Sheet.](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wO6RJOBslmoDm2Wwua50BW2v6XpShcuV/view)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0aa3f9b8-70d8-4e39-9c2a-6c436a17c2d0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4081b917-7649-4238-9b2b-28d9e4f0d59b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete at least 2 practice levels. Practice levels are designed to be around the same level of difficulty, but may ask students to apply skills in different ways."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4081b917-7649-4238-9b2b-28d9e4f0d59b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "83f842ad-8d2c-467b-95c3-c89805eb0292",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Practice",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Practice Levels:** Practice levels give students a chance to apply what they've learned and build fluency with new coding blocks. Students do not need to complete every practice level. Let them choose the ones that match their interests and confidence level.\n\nGiving students real choice often leads to stronger engagement. Encourage them to share and explain the practice levels they completed with the class to reinforce learning.\n\n\n\n**Computational Thinking:** These levels are designed to support computational thinking. As students work, ask which practice they used (such as algorithmic thinking or debugging). This helps prepare them for the wrap-up reflection on computational thinking."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "83f842ad-8d2c-467b-95c3-c89805eb0292",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b54f31be-beee-4e4a-9a9f-49efeff44df1",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the assessment independently",
        "progression_name": "Assessment",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Evaluative Assessment:** Assessment levels appear near the end of a lesson and reflect the key skills students have been building. If you only check one level, this is the one. These can be reviewed after class to help guide your next steps.\n\nFor example:\n\n- If many students struggled, consider starting the next class with a quick review and revisit a skipped practice level.\n\n- If most students succeeded, continue with your planned warm-up or encourage students to try a skipped create level."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b54f31be-beee-4e4a-9a9f-49efeff44df1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "07fb56d7-2f72-49c9-a3b1-1ada4690cccd",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Have students complete as many Create levels as they can.",
        "progression_name": "Create",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Create Levels:** Create levels are designed as extensions to the concepts and skills students learn throughout a lesson. Create levels tend to focus on more open-ended tasks for students to complete, or opportunities to combine several skills from previous lessons together into one program.\n\nCreate levels do **not** need to be completed for students to meet the core objectives of a lesson. Instead, every task in a create level is meant to supplement and enrich the learning objectives of a lesson, but are not required for future lessons. Students can still demonstrate mastery of the objectives of a lesson without completing any of the create levels."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "07fb56d7-2f72-49c9-a3b1-1ada4690cccd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "34682f6b-6708-49c3-b4d8-a6d7ecda145a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec4f1ac7-6949-4565-ad56-db11774d708e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What’s one way you used computational thinking in a level you worked on today?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students reflect on the Practice levels they chose and the strategies they used. Sharing allows them to hear new ideas and learn about levels they may have skipped. Try using a speed pair or similar protocol so students can quickly hear from multiple classmates."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec4f1ac7-6949-4565-ad56-db11774d708e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eb962ee8-abf2-4d88-87ea-95337bdf9091"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f56a863-41d8-4393-8532-660ca104f4a6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After class has ended, use the Teacher Dashboard to review how much progress students made and how well they did on the Assessment level. Some things to notice might be:\n- Did most students make it to the Assessment level, or are there still a lot of empty progress bubbles?\n- Did students make it to the Assessment level, but did not complete it (ie: green outlines with white circles)?\n- Did students finish the Assessment level and continue to the create levels?\n\nBased on these observations, you can adapt the warm up tomorrow to best meet the needs of the class.",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment Level"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f56a863-41d8-4393-8532-660ca104f4a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "243b402e-6906-48f2-9299-c473da275729"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8be5ad69-face-4483-aa59-52a590a398c8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before teaching today's lesson, be sure to use the Teacher Dashboard to assess how students did to make a decision for how to start today's lesson. The Warm-Up for this lesson is adaptable based on how well students did with the Assessment level from the previous lesson. ",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8be5ad69-face-4483-aa59-52a590a398c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22a610dc-e835-4f48-b262-1acc64b0c338"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4afafc3c-6e53-4032-8adc-b693c443ef7b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Start class based on how students performed on yesterday’s Assessment level:\n\n**If many students struggled or didn’t reach the Assessment:** \n- **Whole-Class Reteach** - Walk through a Practice level together, then have students retry the Assessment or move to a Create level.\n\n**If a few students struggled:**\n- **Targeted Support**- Have the class revisit a Create level while you work with students who need extra help.\n\n**If most students did well:**\n- **Move Forward**-  Begin today’s lesson right away to give students more time for practice and deeper exploration.",
        "name": "Differentiated Warm-Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4afafc3c-6e53-4032-8adc-b693c443ef7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "148d749b-d771-418c-85f3-7313390008b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fc7552c9-318d-4383-b40c-0ac1d9c8470f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Set students up for successful Pair Programming by clearly explaining roles, expectations, and when to switch. You can also show [this video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7d_JtyCq1A) to model what it looks like.\n\n**Say:** Today you’ll be working in pairs using Pair Programming. One of you will be the Driver, the person who controls the keyboard and mouse. The other will be the Navigator, who reads the instructions, checks for bugs, and helps think through the steps. Both roles are important, and both of you are responsible for the solution.\nYou must switch roles after each level. This is how both of you learn and stay involved.",
        "name": "Pair Programming",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Digging Deeper**: To learn more about pair programming in the classroom, check out the [K-12 Pair Programming Toolkit](https://www.etr.org/default/assets/File/projects/Pair%20Programming%20Toolkit_FINAL%207_30_19.pdf) from ETR. \n\nTips for Pair Programming Success:\n- Assign or let students choose partners based on your goals.\n- Use a timer, visual cue, or have students switch after completing a level.\n- Circulate to ensure both students are engaged and switching roles.\n- Ask targeted questions to each role. For example, \"Navigator, what is one suggestion you gave the Driver on this level?\"\n- Students can pair through Practice levels, but should complete the Assessment level individually."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fc7552c9-318d-4383-b40c-0ac1d9c8470f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "148d749b-d771-418c-85f3-7313390008b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6a374b6f-4add-468a-aee4-52d582a3b753",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work through the levels in class. Students can use their pair programming partners for support, along with the callout icons in instructions and the example music players.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they complete levels. Most of class is spent within levels, providing lots of opportunity to check-in individually with students as needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Prompts to Build Algorithmic Thinking:** Algorithmic Thinking is all about developing a step-by-step solution to the problem, or the rules to follow to solve the problem. In Music Lab, algorithmic thinking shows up when students follow steps to create a song, such as \"first I'll get my backing beats, then I'll layer in my leads, and finally I'll add the vocals\". Use these questions to help students identify what’s essential in their song or code:\n\n* What steps did you follow to build your song? Could you explain them in order?\n* If you had to teach someone else to build a similar track, what instructions would you give them?\n* Could you create a checklist to build a track like this again?\n\nThese tips come from our Self-Paced Professional Learning module - [click here to see additional tips and learn more about Algorithmic Thinking](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/2/levels/7)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6a374b6f-4add-468a-aee4-52d582a3b753",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9daf625d-68a4-4e4c-a4bb-732c3731c8b4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Predict",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Music Terminology**- The [Musical Terms Anchor Chart - Organizing Music (p.2)](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/12R4e0xxMFBbkyu4gaXbXfwyLba-OjivpRNggZlw8hiE/edit?slide=id.g36d127f8520_0_59#slide=id.g36d127f8520_0_59) could be helpful to deepen student understanding. Additionally, the [Music Terms Glossary](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1wvllTFs0IBWJI8uzfUhuFW4mUYItUK5nmmVjArNRlCM/edit?slide=id.g33d63a1df26_0_86#slide=id.g33d63a1df26_0_86) includes definitions and explanations to support instruction.\n\n**Viewing Example Solutions:** Each level has an example solution that verified teachers can access and view. You can view example solutions by expanding the Teacher Panel from the right-side of the screen, then clicking the blue \"Example Solution\" button. This process is [highlighted in this video](https://www.loom.com/share/36ee8c6709aa4e8dbe2449103e1b07be) and the graphic below\n\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/e2be70507c3a22a08d28a3cd7c8cdd5a-example-solutions.png\" style=\"width: 25%\">"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9daf625d-68a4-4e4c-a4bb-732c3731c8b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ba7a002c-950b-474e-b7fe-9ef17a4b14f2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work, check in by asking clarifying or reflective questions like, *“How are you using play sequential to help your tracks line up the way you want?”* or *“What would happen if you changed this block?”* to promote problem solving.",
        "progression_name": "Play Sequential"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ba7a002c-950b-474e-b7fe-9ef17a4b14f2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e61729c-e3ff-4720-a6e0-16cd91b2e0e0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check-in",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels.\n- Use the tips and guiding questions on the [Sequencing Cheat Sheet.](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wO6RJOBslmoDm2Wwua50BW2v6XpShcuV/view)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e61729c-e3ff-4720-a6e0-16cd91b2e0e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "39475e23-e190-4a14-927f-af85d2d81477",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i>  Circulate & Support: As students work, check in by asking clarifying or reflective questions like, “Can you describe what the rest is doing in this part of your code? Are your tracks lining up the way you want? Could a rest help fix that?”",
        "progression_name": "Rests"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "39475e23-e190-4a14-927f-af85d2d81477",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f79427f8-215c-4d22-a92d-6f320a29c04e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f79427f8-215c-4d22-a92d-6f320a29c04e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "655fe135-2383-4307-8c9a-548fccb26793",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Make sure students split up from pair programming and go back to working independently for the Assessment level.",
        "progression_name": "Assessment",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Evaluative Assessment:** Assessment levels are provided towards the end of a lesson as a culmination of the skills being emphasized in the lesson. If you need to check only one level in this whole lesson, it can be this level. They are designed to be checked after class, allowing you to decide if you want to adjust instruction for the next day's lesson. For example:\n- If most students struggle with the assessment level, it may be worth starting tomorrow's class with a quick review and completing one of the practice levels they skipped in today's lesson.\n- If most students are successful in the assessment level, you can continue with the planned warm-up or you can encourage students to complete one of the challenge levels they may have skipped."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "655fe135-2383-4307-8c9a-548fccb26793",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0125db8-bc23-45f8-b1c3-c6085fafcfa6",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Have students complete as many Create levels as they can.",
        "progression_name": "Create",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**High Ceiling:** Create levels provide opportunities for enrichment for students who complete the progression early or are looking for additional challenges. These levels go above the core concepts from the lesson and should be considered \"extra\". There is always a \"free play\" challenge level for students who want a more open-ended experience in building their songs."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0125db8-bc23-45f8-b1c3-c6085fafcfa6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4cb60eee-c741-4e4e-972c-140bcd15480d",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4cb60eee-c741-4e4e-972c-140bcd15480d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0a2b6572-3ae1-4eae-af6b-3dda1b909705"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e715eef7-5cde-43c9-81a4-2398713683ef",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Watch the [Spotlight: Henny Tha Bizness](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OrrZPzgWPII) video\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What is one example from the video of how Henny combines technology and music? What do the technology tools help him do?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify how Henny uses an editing machine to combine the tracks for songs, similar to how students use music lab. They may also notice how Henny applies effects to track using this technology.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> A record producer is just one example of someone who combines music and technology similar to what we've been doing in music lab. Today, we're going to apply what we've been learning similar to how a record producer works with tracks and artists."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e715eef7-5cde-43c9-81a4-2398713683ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1ef11566-d99f-4a95-95cb-66b011f3a050"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "427d95bd-3bc7-437f-8dca-acd9297ef02d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> We're going to start with a quick review of some skills from this week and a check-in level. Once you've passed the check-in, we'll continue to learn more about Henny and how he uses effects.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Opportunity for Differentiation:** These first few levels are designed to provide an opportunity for differentiation or individual intervention. Students who may have been absent or struggling so far can spend additional time in these levels (or revisiting previous assessments) before continuing to the rest of the lesson. Otherwise, students can complete the quick check-in to reinforce the skills from this unit and then continue to the career spotlight."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "427d95bd-3bc7-437f-8dca-acd9297ef02d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "10541d37-074d-4f1f-a86b-f3d8ed2be8f3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students log into the Skill Review level. These levels are a review of all of the skills students have seen in the last two lessons. \n- If students feel confident in what they've been learning, have them continue to the Check-In level.\n- If students have been absent or need a review, have them review the sublevels before continuing to the Check-In\n- The [Organizing Music Anchor Chart](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RDFizyrovrwzPzZEjapEur2H3mUzfqs4/view?usp=drive_link) may be a helpful resource to share with students at this point",
        "progression_name": "Skill Review"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "10541d37-074d-4f1f-a86b-f3d8ed2be8f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00c5c7bb-422e-4b39-9d8b-10851fd694a1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Check-In",
        "progression_name": "Check-in",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment**: This level is the last assessment before the mini-project in the next lesson - consider checking the level during class and providing targeted intervention if students are struggling. Ideally any lingering issues can be addressed here before continuing to the more open-ended project and the rest of the unit. Use the [Sequencing Cheat Sheet for Teachers](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wO6RJOBslmoDm2Wwua50BW2v6XpShcuV/view) for tips and prompts.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00c5c7bb-422e-4b39-9d8b-10851fd694a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "34c4e044-1a05-43de-b376-8c306e55a72a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students read through the spotlight on Henny Tha Bizness",
        "progression_name": "Spotlight: Henny Tha Bizness, Record Producer"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "34c4e044-1a05-43de-b376-8c306e55a72a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a4a1549c-9ebb-409d-b3db-64a7a561500d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:**  As students work, check in by asking clarifying or reflective questions like, How is the effect you added changing the sound of your song? Or, Which blocks are being affected by this effect? How do you know? ",
        "progression_name": "Effects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a4a1549c-9ebb-409d-b3db-64a7a561500d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f225470-4f6c-4984-82f9-26bc579de3c6",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f225470-4f6c-4984-82f9-26bc579de3c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac694e82-1ee0-49dc-a7e4-aba32d9abca7",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Career Connection:** This reflection is an opportunity for students to make a connection between their own future story and the career spotlight. Consider additional ways you want to explore connecting students to careers in computer science or how students can be exposed to professionals currently working in computer science or music careers, such as [Amazon's Career Tours](https://www.amazonfutureengineer.com/careertours) experiences."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac694e82-1ee0-49dc-a7e4-aba32d9abca7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3746e40e-3db0-4475-ab73-c9c97a09a469",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Create"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3746e40e-3db0-4475-ab73-c9c97a09a469",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68668a91-74f5-4a91-a4c0-609ba1cf1933"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4da69b68-b2d0-4d08-b992-56dfe6149b82",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Share Out:** Have students share their work with their peers in some way. Their peers can provide feedback using \"I like...\" and \"What if...\" sentence stems to provide positive constructive feedback. Some options could be:\n- **Class Shareout:** Ask for volunteers and let them share their songs with the whole class, then choose 2-3 students to provide feedback\n- **Pair Networking:** Have students pair up and share their songs and provide feedback, then swap to a new pair\n- **Gallery Walk:** Have students leave their song open on their computer, then walk around and visit other songs. Students carry post-it notes with them and leave feedback on any students they visit."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4da69b68-b2d0-4d08-b992-56dfe6149b82",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bdb67a89-0db2-4576-8e37-d7eec6e8321b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00766756-513b-4fc2-8361-ef67165910cc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After reviewing the project guide and rubric, you can view an exemplar for this project in our self-paced professional learning course. [**Click here to view the exemplar**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/2/levels/20)",
        "name": "Project Exemplar"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00766756-513b-4fc2-8361-ef67165910cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff5bc315-c4df-428a-8c90-0625032e4969"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e6acd53-4963-4e95-bed4-fb14997a939e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Who is a character in a movie or show who has a distinctive musical theme? Where every time you hear the music, you think of that character?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** It may take some time for students to think of examples here, but once they hear a few they may be more likely to come up with additional examples. Another way to frame this question is: if you were walking by a room and heard this musical theme, you'd know what movie or show someone was watching Some examples you could supply are:\n- [Bluey](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8nv1m-aTCZI) has a very distinctive theme song\n- [Harry Potter](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wtHra9tFISY) has a distinctive theme\n- Baseball players or wrestlers have distinctive music for when they enter an arena\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Today we're going to apply everything we've learned so far to create Walk-Up songs for different characters in books or TV shows! In order to make these songs, we're going to learn about a new feature in music lab: Triggers!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e6acd53-4963-4e95-bed4-fb14997a939e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "26cb000c-eb3e-48df-b10c-7174f52dbd81"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6c502ecf-42f1-4fcb-bae7-54717371a13b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Have students start with exploring the student project examples. Encourage them to discuss what they notice, wonder and like about the projects",
        "progression_name": "Example Projects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6c502ecf-42f1-4fcb-bae7-54717371a13b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "58fdc50c-414a-467f-8733-735b3b35d309",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Pass out a copy of the [Walk Up Songs Activity Guide](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-NOQXuyOA4TXy2X4oACt97K0f64h2TlkP2tc3-YQKRI/edit) to each student\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Overview as a class\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Define portion of the activity guide\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students return to Music Lab to learn more about triggers.",
        "progression_name": "Triggers"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "58fdc50c-414a-467f-8733-735b3b35d309",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "078d522d-3810-4469-a5e0-df287e5a1a13",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Do This: Have students complete the Prepare section of their activity guide. Use this level to plan which tracks they will use!\n\nRemind students of the [Track Types anchor chart](https://drive.google.com/file/d/16ONMCb6K-cWYW_WVRwYXJM6TXbCI6Okz/view?usp=drive_link) to use as a guide to plan their tracks.\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Prepare"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "078d522d-3810-4469-a5e0-df287e5a1a13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "632d6764-c78d-41eb-86f7-e68692e0ef22",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Approve:** As students complete their project plan, circulate to give them a quick review and a thumbs-up. Hand them the [Walk Up Songs Rubric](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1poW9kQYsXnBX2w7jCKhN9qjTbJ52qRDrn8jZf62S3-g/edit?tab=t.0) once their plan is solid. Students do not need to stop and wait for you."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "632d6764-c78d-41eb-86f7-e68692e0ef22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d797755-ed3e-444f-b102-0106c8cc5b5f",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Walk-Up Songs"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d797755-ed3e-444f-b102-0106c8cc5b5f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9f594c4-d5bb-4803-ba08-25933acc4446",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Students who finish their walk-up songs can participate in this Partner Game:\n- Tell your partners who your three characters are and describe the character's personalities.\n- Play one of your Walk-Up songs without saying which character it belongs to.\n- Allow your partner to match the song to a character.\n- Ask them to explain their choice.\n- If they guess wrong, listen to their explanation and adjust your code to make the song fit the character better.\n- Repeat with new partners until someone guesses all three correctly!",
        "progression_name": "(Optional) Partner Game"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9f594c4-d5bb-4803-ba08-25933acc4446",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28fb0ac1-3391-4a57-92b6-7bc3b1e8f021",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28fb0ac1-3391-4a57-92b6-7bc3b1e8f021",
        "lesson_activity.key": "580a7631-8c4a-4b38-8de6-83deaf3d3d6d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "988c4658-5710-44d0-aedf-ecb5cc99bcf5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Share Out:** Have students share their work with their peers in some way. Their peers can provide feedback using \"I like...\" and \"What if...\" sentence stems to provide positive constructive feedback. Some options could be:\n- **Class Shareout:** Ask for volunteers and let them share their songs with the whole class, then choose 2-3 students to provide feedback\n- **Pair Networking:** Have students pair up and share their songs and provide feedback, then swap to a new pair\n- **Gallery Walk:** Have students leave their song open on their computer, then walk around and visit other songs. Students carry post-it notes with them and leave feedback on any students they visit."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "988c4658-5710-44d0-aedf-ecb5cc99bcf5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7ed29975-3960-4123-acaa-c7eaf2ea3f7d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eaffa71f-0849-4e17-816a-551558de8280",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The next set of lessons introduces **Loops** with brand new blocks and programming strategies. Feel prepared to teach these lessons by reviewing our Self-Paced Professional Learning specifically for these lessons - in under 30 minutes! [**Click here to start now!**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/3/levels/1)",
        "name": "Just-In-Time Professional Learning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eaffa71f-0849-4e17-816a-551558de8280",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cadb58b0-1558-47de-b274-c82c5de15a29"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "538f3d08-6f9c-4680-8c51-12b6997f521b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Choose from one of the following videos to show the class:\n- [Owen Pallett - Live on KEXP](https://youtu.be/kz4KASHRsT4?t=1440) (start at 24:00 - This is The Dream of Win and Regine)\n- [Carolina Eyck - Ennio Morricone cover with Theramin and Voice](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ajM4vYCZMZk)\n- [Hailey Knox - New Guitar Loop](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j4iqfYEx23c)\n- [Reggie Watts - I Just Want To](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=344OpaQCAQI)\n\nEach video features an artist who uses a loop pedal to construct the backing tracks for their songs live as the song is being performed. You may decide to only show part of the video (usually up a minute) during a sequence that highlights this feature.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**A Longer Example:** If you have the time in class, you can consider showing a longer clip of [Imogen Heap - Tiny Desk Concert](https://youtu.be/3QtklTXbKUQ?t=600) starting at 10:00. This clip is unique because Imogen Heap developed her own hardware and software that allows her to use gloves onstage to control effects with her voice. From 10:00-13:00, she demonstrates how the hardware and software work together to create effects on her voice live in front of audiences, and then at 13:00 she performs a song using the gloves. Consider showing this clip if you've also discussed hardware and software in your class, or wanted to dive deeper into how effects can be used with music."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "538f3d08-6f9c-4680-8c51-12b6997f521b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "45212074-8ee5-46fe-8a13-f8cb84905ae5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cb167632-2f1a-4fa0-beee-3fd133dc82e9",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What is unique about how this artist is making the backing track under their vocals?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This question has a straightforward answer - the artist is 'looping' sounds from their voice or instrument to create the backing track - but the discussion can be open-ended and highlight aspects of the performance that students find intriguing. For example, Reggie Watts and Kishi Bashi use effects as part of their performance and students may connect this to the previous lesson. Or students may be intrigued by the live element of the performance and how the sounds are created \"on the fly\".\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> This performance highlights a new concept we'll explore today: how to create loops in our code. By using loops, we can easily repeat certain tracks to play underneath our main vocals or other tracks."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cb167632-2f1a-4fa0-beee-3fd133dc82e9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "45212074-8ee5-46fe-8a13-f8cb84905ae5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "895baa73-1afe-4848-b427-11a89977ee94",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Predict level. Have students respond to the two questions within the level:\n- Write down anything you **notice** about the code\n- Make a **prediction** - what do you think will happen when you press Run?\n\nOnce students have made a prediction, they can press Run to see the result.",
        "progression_name": "Predict",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**No Wrong Answers** - These questions are intentionally structured to encourage \"no wrong answer\" thinking, which invites students to make unstructured observations and participate in class discussions. These predict levels are based on the PRIMM pedagogy for teaching coding, which shows increased engagement and ownership when students are asked to form hypotheses about code before seeing it in action. As you structure these discussions, ensure all students feel supported in participating and try to avoid confirming or denying any ideas and instead letting students make those observations themselves when running the code."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "895baa73-1afe-4848-b427-11a89977ee94",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2ef140a0-cc17-4e14-9101-d8b215d6a11d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Once the class has seen the code, lead a discussion about what went as expected and what was surprising. Explicitly explain how the `repeat` block works and ensure students understand why the code behaves the way it does before continuing. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2ef140a0-cc17-4e14-9101-d8b215d6a11d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98ee64dc-92c1-458b-b005-512e519006cf",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students should work through the Investigate levels independently or with a partner using Pair Programming. This allows you to circulate and provide targeted support. Your goal is to check in with every student or pair, which is a high-impact practice for boosting engagement.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Introducing Shadow Blocks**: This lesson introduces a new pedagogical tool for teaching students code: _shadow blocks_. These are blocks in the workspace that represent \"old code\" before we learned updated shortcuts - for example, duplicating the same `play` blocks over and over before we learned about the `repeat` blocks. Shadow blocks help students notice patterns and make plans when completing levels.\n\nFor a detailed overview of shadow blocks and how they can help students with planning, debugging, and pattern observations: [watch this video overview of shadow blocks](https://www.loom.com/share/577e64f8ec2742788b0c4963de47a07c)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98ee64dc-92c1-458b-b005-512e519006cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ff65722-f1d2-45b0-ad86-c79ed4d86572",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work independently, your presence and encouragement can have a powerful impact. A simple check-in can boost confidence, uncover misunderstandings, or spark deeper thinking. Use this time to:\n\n- Notice patterns then use this info to tailor your next move.\n- Ask open-ended questions to prompt reflection and reasoning.\n- Celebrate progress: Point out creative approaches or persistence, even if a solution isn't perfect yet.\n\nIf students are stuck, guide them to:\n- Re-read the step-by-step instructions and click the icons for hints\n- Listen to the example song for clues\n- Try one idea and observe what happens\n\n**<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i>  Do This (Optional):** Once enough students have completed the Investigate levels, consider regrouping to talk through the levels as a class. This is a good opportunity to cement student thinking on key concepts from the lesson while also elevating student voices by calling on students to help you complete levels in front of the class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ff65722-f1d2-45b0-ad86-c79ed4d86572",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "836f1ea7-494b-430f-9abd-67fd0de9d3a2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Check-In level. The remaining levels can be completed independently at students' own pace.",
        "progression_name": "Check-in",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels.\n- Use the tips and guiding questions on the [Loops Cheat Sheet.](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hdfC0eaWgQAljeCJK209qWt_uCoWQsAk/view)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "836f1ea7-494b-430f-9abd-67fd0de9d3a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "27a3a0f4-7e9a-48ba-83b3-aeb0fc87bc93",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete at least 2 practice levels. Practice levels are designed to be around the same level of difficulty, but may ask students to apply skills in different ways.",
        "progression_name": "Practice",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Practice Levels:** Practice levels are designed for students to apply their knowledge from the previous levels and develop fluency in using the new blocks of code to solve problems. Students can choose which practice levels they would like to complete, and it’s not necessary for a student to complete each practice level before continuing.\n\nStudents tend to be more engaged and respond better when they have an authentic choice about how to continue their learning. Allow students to choose practice levels according to their interests and level of comfort, and consider providing opportunities for students to demonstrate and explain their solutions to the practice levels they chose to the entire class.\n\n**Computational Thinking:** Practice levels intentionally incorporate computational thinking practices - as students complete levels, you can ask about the particular computational thinking practice they used in the level (for example: algorithmic thinking or debugging). This will also help prime students for the wrap-up reflection on computational thinking practices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "27a3a0f4-7e9a-48ba-83b3-aeb0fc87bc93",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "018f6f4f-8f9c-4b3e-a9f9-9cfc237221c6",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the assessment independently",
        "progression_name": "Assessment",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Evaluative Assessment:** Assessment levels are provided towards the end of a lesson as a culmination of the skills being emphasized in the lesson. If you need to check only one level in this whole lesson, it can be this level. They are designed to be checked after class, allowing you to decide if you want to adjust instruction for the next day's lesson. For example:\n- If most students struggle with the assessment level, it may be worth starting tomorrow's class with a quick review and completing one of the practice levels they skipped in today's lesson.\n- If most students are successful in the assessment level, you can continue with the planned warm-up or you can encourage students to complete one of the create levels they may have skipped."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "018f6f4f-8f9c-4b3e-a9f9-9cfc237221c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9ef03f8-e3e6-4b80-971a-56caa48036af",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Have students complete as many Create levels as they can.",
        "progression_name": "Create",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Create Levels:** Create levels are designed as extensions to the concepts and skills students learn throughout a lesson. Create levels tend to focus on more open-ended tasks for students to complete, or opportunities to combine several skills from previous lessons together into one program.\n\nCreate levels do **not** need to be completed for students to meet the core objectives of a lesson. Instead, every task in a create level is meant to supplement and enrich the learning objectives of a lesson, but are not required for future lessons. Students can still demonstrate mastery of the objectives of a lesson without completing any of the create levels."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b9ef03f8-e3e6-4b80-971a-56caa48036af",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9e2781df-5c84-45d2-a036-3979f3c55011"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ae799077-58eb-4184-958b-1a7d1c2edf02",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Turn & Talk - What's an example of how you used computational thinking in one of the levels today?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should refer back to the Practice levels they completed and the strategies highlighted in each level. By sharing out, students get to hear about choice levels they may have skipped and get new ideas for how computational thinking is tied to building songs with code. Consider having students complete this discussion using the speed pair protocol or another strategy where students can hear many different perspectives quickly"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ae799077-58eb-4184-958b-1a7d1c2edf02",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770f83f5-76a5-4990-a3bb-968c42e2a978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f847d72f-62f9-475b-ab5c-2e56b7c6f4d5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After class has ended, use the Teacher Dashboard to review how much progress students made and how well they did on the Assessment level. Some things to notice might be:\n- Did most students make it to the Assessment level, or are there still a lot of empty progress bubbles?\n- Did students make it to the Assessment level, but did not complete it (ie: green outlines with white circles)?\n- Did students finish the Assessment level and continue to the create levels?\n\nBased on these observations, you can adapt the warm up tomorrow to best meet the needs of the class.",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment Level"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f847d72f-62f9-475b-ab5c-2e56b7c6f4d5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "62202f5f-8333-42e3-9bb5-8b4c4a535b2f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20f77a7b-5285-4567-b588-69667880c884",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before teaching today's lesson, be sure to use the Teacher Dashboard to assess how students did to make a decision for how to start today's lesson. The Warm-Up for this lesson is adaptable based on how well students did with the Assessment level from the previous lesson. ",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20f77a7b-5285-4567-b588-69667880c884",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c7ef2570-4c0d-4aad-90ee-6a7cb6aefa62"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6c55f721-f417-45ea-a122-c0ea9426becd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Start class based on how students performed on yesterday’s Assessment level:\n\n**If many students struggled or didn’t reach the Assessment:** \n- **Whole-Class Reteach** - Walk through a Practice level together, then have students retry the Assessment or move to a Create level.\n\n**If a few students struggled:**\n- **Targeted Support**- Have the class revisit a Create level while you work with students who need extra help.\n\n**If most students did well:**\n- **Move Forward**-  Begin today’s lesson right away to give students more time for practice and deeper exploration.",
        "name": "Differentiated Warm-Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6c55f721-f417-45ea-a122-c0ea9426becd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "101324b3-7857-498b-9d9c-242c03cd3b9f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86d8b2d2-3864-4a0d-a895-4ad0f399b9f0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Set students up for successful Pair Programming by clearly explaining roles, expectations, and when to switch. You can also show [this video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7d_JtyCq1A) to model what it looks like.\n\n**Say:** Today you’ll be working in pairs using Pair Programming. One of you will be the Driver, the person who controls the keyboard and mouse. The other will be the Navigator, who reads the instructions, checks for bugs, and helps think through the steps. Both roles are important, and both of you are responsible for the solution.\nYou must switch roles after each level. This is how both of you learn and stay involved.",
        "name": "Pair Programming",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Digging Deeper**: To learn more about pair programming in the classroom, check out the [K-12 Pair Programming Toolkit](https://www.etr.org/default/assets/File/projects/Pair%20Programming%20Toolkit_FINAL%207_30_19.pdf) from ETR. \n\nTips for Pair Programming Success:\n- Assign or let students choose partners based on your goals.\n- Use a timer, visual cue, or have students switch after completing a level.\n- Circulate to ensure both students are engaged and switching roles.\n- Ask targeted questions to each role. For example, \"Navigator, what is one suggestion you gave the Driver on this level?\"\n- Students can pair through Practice levels, but should complete the Assessment level individually."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86d8b2d2-3864-4a0d-a895-4ad0f399b9f0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "101324b3-7857-498b-9d9c-242c03cd3b9f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d4b949f-1663-48d5-a3e8-d7f7b452b5a6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work through the levels in class. Students can use their pair programming partners for support, along with the callout icons in instructions and the example music players.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they complete levels. Most of class is spent within levels, providing lots of opportunity to check-in individually with students as needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Prompts to Build Pattern Recognition:** Pattern recognition is one of the key practices in computational thinking. In Music Lab, patterns can show up in track order, rhythm, and how certain song sections are structured. Helping students _notice and name_ these patterns gives them powerful tools for coding and creativity. Use questions like these to encourage students to think like pattern-spotters:\n\n- What parts of this song repeat? Can you show it in the code?\n- Where do you see the same blocks used more than once?\n- Do any instruments or beats create a repeating structure in this song?\n\nThese tips come from our Self-Paced Professional Learning module - [click here to see additional tips and learn more about Pattern Recognition](studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/3/levels/7)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d4b949f-1663-48d5-a3e8-d7f7b452b5a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c81661dd-fe27-45f4-872a-db7f2609613d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Loops with Lyrics"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c81661dd-fe27-45f4-872a-db7f2609613d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4d3577c8-a7aa-4496-b696-2710b8f20bc1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work, check in by asking clarifying or reflective questions like, *What pattern is your loop creating in your song?* or *Could you simplify your code by using a loop inside a loop? Where?* ",
        "progression_name": "Nested Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4d3577c8-a7aa-4496-b696-2710b8f20bc1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e0067574-e695-4a6a-a48a-54b483c05a61",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check-in",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels.\n- Use the tips and guiding questions on the [Sequencing Cheat Sheet.](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wO6RJOBslmoDm2Wwua50BW2v6XpShcuV/view)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e0067574-e695-4a6a-a48a-54b483c05a61",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c4714f70-191f-4c72-9638-988a89405358",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Loops with Rests"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c4714f70-191f-4c72-9638-988a89405358",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f535c5f0-683b-45fd-987b-8db2237c39c0",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work, check in by asking clarifying or reflective questions like, *How are you using rests to shift the timing of your loop?* or *Can you hear a difference between a loop with no rests and a loop with rests added? What stands out?*",
        "progression_name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f535c5f0-683b-45fd-987b-8db2237c39c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "193478eb-9a35-4efc-9636-c7e3f643003b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Make sure students split up from pair programming and go back to working independently for the Assessment level.",
        "progression_name": "Assessment",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Evaluative Assessment:** Assessment levels are provided towards the end of a lesson as a culmination of the skills being emphasized in the lesson. If you need to check only one level in this whole lesson, it can be this level. They are designed to be checked after class, allowing you to decide if you want to adjust instruction for the next day's lesson. For example:\n- If most students struggle with the assessment level, it may be worth starting tomorrow's class with a quick review and completing one of the practice levels they skipped in today's lesson.\n- If most students are successful in the assessment level, you can continue with the planned warm-up or you can encourage students to complete one of the challenge levels they may have skipped."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "193478eb-9a35-4efc-9636-c7e3f643003b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36edd498-91bd-4736-84f0-8b5a4b7db91b",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Have students complete as many Create levels as they can.",
        "progression_name": "Create"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36edd498-91bd-4736-84f0-8b5a4b7db91b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f731f0e2-1b98-442d-8fb8-b5fbc8df52ec"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2f900fa-3d38-455f-9ed5-302b072fd9d1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Watch the [Spotlight: Roxanne Harris, Creative Coder](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MDtQjObQ8yY) video\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What is one example from the video of how Roxanne combines music and technology?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** There are many examples from the video, such as how Roxanne uses code to create music as well as how she structures her live performances. Students may also notice the ways Roxanne describes how her process is creative and personal, invoking her personal passions for music and code.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Roxanne is an artist who combines music and code for her performances, which is one example of how to combine music and technology beyond what we've been learning in music lab. Today, we're going to apply what we've been learning similar to how Roxanne creates her live performances."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2f900fa-3d38-455f-9ed5-302b072fd9d1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "39fcb45b-ec38-48f3-8db3-7f06245af6a2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "866c960c-072f-4422-a588-f81c09a027be",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> We're going to start with a quick review of some skills from this week and a check-in level. Once you've passed the check-in, we'll continue to learn more about Roxanne and how she does live coding.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Opportunity for Differentiation:** These first few levels are designed to provide an opportunity for differentiation or individual intervention. Students who may have been absent or struggling so far can spend additional time in these levels (or revisiting previous assessments) before continuing to the rest of the lesson. Otherwise, students can complete the quick check-in to reinforce the skills from this unit and then continue to the career spotlight."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "866c960c-072f-4422-a588-f81c09a027be",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0540ac87-4b96-4e42-8f24-9692a7265fb6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students log into the Skill Review level. These levels are a review of all of the skills students have seen in the last two lessons. \n- If students feel confident in what they've been learning, have them continue to the Check-In level.\n- If students have been absent or need a review, have them review the sublevels before continuing to the Check-In",
        "progression_name": "Skill Review"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0540ac87-4b96-4e42-8f24-9692a7265fb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9a38b755-b6f4-41c4-97d4-634bd1e5e9c6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Check-In",
        "progression_name": "Check-In",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment**: This level is the last assessment before the mini-project in the next lesson - consider checking the level during class and providing targeted intervention if students are struggling. Ideally any lingering issues can be addressed here before continuing to the more open-ended project and the rest of the unit. Use the [Loops Cheat Sheet for Teachers](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hdfC0eaWgQAljeCJK209qWt_uCoWQsAk/view) for tips and prompts.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9a38b755-b6f4-41c4-97d4-634bd1e5e9c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7384f635-a6fa-442b-8415-281769e86cff",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students read through the spotlight on Roxanne Harris",
        "progression_name": "Spotlight: Roxanne Harris, Creative Coder"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7384f635-a6fa-442b-8415-281769e86cff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c971ba6e-41c3-47cf-9572-b2f3f9b46eee",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue through the remaining levels in the lesson. Students will learn about how to interact with Music Lab to perform \"live performances\".",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Overview of Live Coding:** These levels require students to make edits to the code _as the music is playing_, similar to what Roxanne does in her performances. This may be tricky to visualize or be sure you're \"doing the level correctly\" since it requires a live action. To help with this, [please watch this video overview of Live Coding for these levels](https://www.loom.com/share/0cefdcdd98244527a3d0a3a77d4078eb).\n\nThis also means it's not possible to review student code after the lesson, since you won't be able to see the decisions they made \"live\". As such, consider how you want to circulate and interact with students during this lesson to emphasize the live aspect."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c971ba6e-41c3-47cf-9572-b2f3f9b46eee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "27d01ea1-cab7-4bf1-980c-0be3bbb923b2",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Live Coding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "27d01ea1-cab7-4bf1-980c-0be3bbb923b2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a05114fc-8a3d-4f12-82f5-1796095784f4",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Guiding Questions for Circulation During Live Coding**\n- **What was your plan and how did it change while performing?** *Helps students reflect on planning vs. improvisation.*\n- **What did you notice when you added or removed sounds?**   *Promotes observation and awareness of timing and impact.*\n- **Did you try anything unexpected? How did it sound?** *Encourages risk-taking and reflection on creative choices.*\n- **What moment felt the most exciting or worked best?** *Helps students identify personal wins and build confidence.*\n- **What role does each sound play in your track?** *Deepens thinking around musical structure and intent.*\n- **How are you deciding when to bring sounds in or out?** *Supports development of timing and improvisation instincts.*",
        "progression_name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a05114fc-8a3d-4f12-82f5-1796095784f4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e2f534bc-d5f1-4722-a5d4-0789c3bb31fa",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Career Connection:** This reflection is an opportunity for students to make a connection between their own future story and the career spotlight. Consider additional ways you want to explore connecting students to careers in computer science or how students can be exposed to professionals currently working in computer science or music careers, such as [Amazon's Career Tours](https://www.amazonfutureengineer.com/careertours) experiences."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e2f534bc-d5f1-4722-a5d4-0789c3bb31fa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c03f843b-fd58-4715-9177-2b56145d944a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Create"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c03f843b-fd58-4715-9177-2b56145d944a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "513ba17e-bbe0-46e1-b5a4-68b50e7cb39a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11b57d12-2e94-49ae-bce9-680a50fc2565",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Share Out:** Have students share their work with their peers in some way. Their peers can provide feedback using \"I like...\" and \"What if...\" sentence stems to provide positive constructive feedback. Some options could be:\n- **Class Shareout:** Ask for volunteers and let them share their songs with the whole class, then choose 2-3 students to provide feedback\n- **Pair Networking:** Have students pair up and share their songs and provide feedback, then swap to a new pair\n- **Gallery Walk:** Have students leave their song open on their computer, then walk around and visit other songs. Students carry post-it notes with them and leave feedback on any students they visit."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11b57d12-2e94-49ae-bce9-680a50fc2565",
        "lesson_activity.key": "454f47dc-b7e0-477b-a037-15826a90551a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6a2e3f0-5e28-4e61-8040-5b4a608b079e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After reviewing the project guide and rubric, you can view an exemplar for this project in our self-paced professional learning course. [**Click here to view the exemplar**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/3/levels/19)",
        "name": "Project Exemplar"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6a2e3f0-5e28-4e61-8040-5b4a608b079e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6d3c5853-3798-40c7-a5c5-c3211a05cce4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f1d97bf-114f-4c87-8886-c8be4d9be615",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What's an example of something visual that you've seen loop forever? What are those visuals usually trying to communicate?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** It may take some time for students to think of examples here, but once they hear a few they may be more likely to come up with additional examples. Once clear example are gifs or memes, which usually try to communicate something silly or funny but can also provide satire or social commentary. Students may also think of public safety animations, such as a crossing-guard animation saying it is okay to cross or you need to stop. These types of visuals communicate safety information. When it seems like students have surfaced several examples, continue with the discussion\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display:** Show the slide with several cat GIFs on it\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Today we're going to combine visual loops and sound loops by adding a looped backing track to a cat GIF of your choice. You will need to determine the mood or vibe of your particular gif and create a song that matches this mood. To make things more interesting, we're also going to learn how we can randomize tracks in a song to add to make our song more unexpected."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f1d97bf-114f-4c87-8886-c8be4d9be615",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64a571f3-b485-4b16-aa70-74434b3c3429"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e9b20161-e034-42d7-8146-661a52ad2278",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students start with exploring the student project examples. Encourage them to discuss what they notice, wonder and like about the projects",
        "progression_name": "Example Projects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9b20161-e034-42d7-8146-661a52ad2278",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e2deaa1c-9678-4961-ad37-33aee7de3e2f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8aa7a421-59a0-4038-a13d-c2011d2ee199",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Pass out a copy of the [Cat GIFs Activity Guide](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JQWXQ39-DKoE2gbwLi7v-BdV0Dcn3Z9IMY0515-pKVI/edit) to each student\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the Overview as a class\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the Define portion of the activity guide\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students return to Music Lab to learn about the Play Random and complete the Prepare portion of the activity guide",
        "progression_name": "Play Random"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8aa7a421-59a0-4038-a13d-c2011d2ee199",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e2deaa1c-9678-4961-ad37-33aee7de3e2f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c89e1a4c-1cc8-483c-bf54-eca170d055e7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students complete the Prepare section of their activity guide. Use this level to plan which tracks they will use!\n\nRemind students of the Track Types anchor chart to use as a guide to plan their tracks.",
        "progression_name": "Prepare"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c89e1a4c-1cc8-483c-bf54-eca170d055e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e2deaa1c-9678-4961-ad37-33aee7de3e2f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "593be110-eba5-49cf-ae1f-7dba3a261f4d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Approve:** As students complete their project plan, circulate to give them a quick review and a thumbs-up. Hand them the [Cat GIF Loops Rubric](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ZW8gD3eA3lXAur9_PSC8nL2h6VJrcW2fBC3rxwm8Moc/edit?tab=t.0) once their plan is solid. Students do not need to stop and wait for you..",
        "progression_name": "Musical Cat GIFs"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "593be110-eba5-49cf-ae1f-7dba3a261f4d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e2deaa1c-9678-4961-ad37-33aee7de3e2f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1895b19d-78a5-4a6e-b509-5e74c83bef58",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Share Out:** Have students share their work with their peers in some way. Their peers can provide feedback using \"I like...\" and \"What if...\" sentence stems to provide positive constructive feedback. Some options could be:\n- **Class Shareout:** Ask for volunteers and let them share their songs with the whole class, then choose 2-3 students to provide feedback\n- **Pair Networking:** Have students pair up and share their songs and provide feedback, then swap to a new pair\n- **Gallery Walk:** Have students leave their song open on their computer, then walk around and visit other songs. Students carry post-it notes with them and leave feedback on any students they visit."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1895b19d-78a5-4a6e-b509-5e74c83bef58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "025ce0af-f964-4be6-974a-bbd4a8407003"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9d5c4664-62a8-49bf-8685-26068e40ec85",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The next set of lessons introduces **Functions** with brand new blocks and programming strategies. Feel prepared to teach these lessons by reviewing our Self-Paced Professional Learning specifically for these lessons - in under 30 minutes! [**Click here to start now!**](https://studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/4/levels/1)",
        "name": "Just-In-Time Professional Learning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9d5c4664-62a8-49bf-8685-26068e40ec85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9a8f2c3e-7ad5-402a-ab05-615ab2e82162"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bc294012-211c-4760-b36a-e2f5078e0d77",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-headphones\"></i> **Listen**: Choose one of the mashup videos from this Youtube Playlist to have the class listen to: [35 Years of Music Remixed Year by Year](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLqrkwSi3LHneR8zHLgCnuFLCE76Qwm2iE).\n\n**Disclaimer:** Listen to the song fully before playing for students. We do not recommend showing the video since the visual is inconsequential to the song. As an alternative to this playlist: find any song that is a \"mashup\" of at least 3 different songs where different parts of songs are cut together (as opposed to a medley, where parts of songs are sung in a row).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Think, Pair, Share:** How many songs could you identify in the mashup? How could you tell?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students may have fun discussing the first part of this prompt, but the second part is what will tie into the lesson. Students may identify unique aspects of songs that \"stand out\", like a particular drumline or guitar solo or verse. Emphasize how identifying these components required focusing on what was important and \"tuning out\" the other parts of the song you may not have recognized.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Songs have unique structures, and our brain can compartmentalize the unique parts of songs to help recognize them later. Today we're going to learn how to do something similar in code - separate out songs into parts called functions and use those functions to build the complete song."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bc294012-211c-4760-b36a-e2f5078e0d77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "84550954-5df2-42fc-a096-8fbebf8f8144"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d66a7d99-3214-42c9-ae16-bd6f03ba6991",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Predict level. Have students respond to the two questions within the level:\n- Write down anything you **notice** about the code\n- Make a **prediction** - what do you think will happen when you press Run?\n\nOnce students have made a prediction, they can press Run to see the result.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**No Wrong Answers** - These questions are intentionally structured to encourage \"no wrong answer\" thinking, which invites students to make unstructured observations and participate in class discussions. These predict levels are based on the PRIMM pedagogy for teaching coding, which shows increased engagement and ownership when students are asked to form hypotheses about code before seeing it in action. As you structure these discussions, ensure all students feel supported in participating and try to avoid confirming or denying any ideas and instead letting students make those observations themselves when running the code.\n\n**Music Terminology**- A shared vocabulary is the foundation of meaningful collaboration. The first page of this [Anchor Chart set](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/12R4e0xxMFBbkyu4gaXbXfwyLba-OjivpRNggZlw8hiE/edit?usp=sharing) could be a powerful resource to share with students at this point. Additionally, the [Music Terms Glossary](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1wvllTFs0IBWJI8uzfUhuFW4mUYItUK5nmmVjArNRlCM/edit?usp=sharing) includes definitions and explanations to support instruction.  "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d66a7d99-3214-42c9-ae16-bd6f03ba6991",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "071d7aca-514a-4032-87a9-0539966fb4ee",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Predict"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "071d7aca-514a-4032-87a9-0539966fb4ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ba13a7b4-bfea-4f4c-8346-e828664fb0b6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Once the class has seen the code, lead a discussion about what went as expected and what was surprising. Explicitly explain how the `function` block works. Ensure students understand why the code behaves the way it does before continuing. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ba13a7b4-bfea-4f4c-8346-e828664fb0b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a758376-12a6-471c-9bae-0e7edfce9412",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students should work through the Investigate levels independently or with a partner. This allows you to circulate and provide targeted support. Your goal is to check in with every student or pair, which is a high-impact practice for boosting engagement.",
        "progression_name": "Investigate"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a758376-12a6-471c-9bae-0e7edfce9412",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "960de339-c8fd-46fa-870f-577e94e8399b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work independently, your presence and encouragement can have a powerful impact. A simple check-in can boost confidence, uncover misunderstandings, or spark deeper thinking. Use this time to:\n\n- Notice patterns then use this info to tailor your next move.\n- Ask open-ended questions to prompt reflection and reasoning.\n- Celebrate progress: Point out creative approaches or persistence, even if a solution isn't perfect yet.\n\nIf students are stuck, guide them to:\n- Re-read the step-by-step instructions and click the icons for hints\n- Listen to the example song for clues\n- Try one idea and observe what happens\n\n**<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i>  Do This (Optional):** Once enough students have completed the Investigate levels, consider regrouping to talk through the levels as a class. This is a good opportunity to cement student thinking on key concepts from the lesson while also elevating student voices by calling on students to help you complete levels in front of the class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "960de339-c8fd-46fa-870f-577e94e8399b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e0d21b6-565c-421a-91b6-016f1ddf90bf",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students continue to the Check-In level. The remaining levels can be completed independently at students' own pace.",
        "progression_name": "Check-In",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels.\n- Use the tips and guiding questions on the [Functions Cheat Sheet.](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1PFQdLhk1Yi4HdzBmI17N31GtybQcm2Nm/view)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e0d21b6-565c-421a-91b6-016f1ddf90bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "197e4d64-4b93-4ae5-b548-3ccca1e0fb8d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete at least 2 practice levels. Practice levels are designed to be around the same level of difficulty, but may ask students to apply skills in different ways.",
        "progression_name": "Practice",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Practice Levels:** Practice levels are designed for students to apply their knowledge from the previous levels and develop fluency in using the new blocks of code to solve problems. Students can choose which practice levels they would like to complete, and it’s not necessary for a student to complete each practice level before continuing.\n\nStudents tend to be more engaged and respond better when they have an authentic choice about how to continue their learning. Allow students to choose practice levels according to their interests and level of comfort, and consider providing opportunities for students to demonstrate and explain their solutions to the practice levels they chose to the entire class.\n\n**Computational Thinking:** Practice levels intentionally incorporate computational thinking practices - as students complete levels, you can ask about the particular computational thinking practice they used in the level (for example: algorithmic thinking or debugging). This will also help prime students for the wrap-up reflection on computational thinking practices."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "197e4d64-4b93-4ae5-b548-3ccca1e0fb8d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "06be6f47-193f-402e-bda1-c13776820cd3",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the assessment independently",
        "progression_name": "Assessment",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Evaluative Assessment:** Assessment levels are provided towards the end of a lesson as a culmination of the skills being emphasized in the lesson. If you need to check only one level in this whole lesson, it can be this level. They are designed to be checked after class, allowing you to decide if you want to adjust instruction for the next day's lesson. For example:\n- If most students struggle with the assessment level, it may be worth starting tomorrow's class with a quick review and completing one of the practice levels they skipped in today's lesson.\n- If most students are successful in the assessment level, you can continue with the planned warm-up or you can encourage students to complete one of the create levels they may have skipped."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "06be6f47-193f-402e-bda1-c13776820cd3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "537c8096-6139-4dac-a8b1-24f9561c0499",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **(Optional) Do This:** Have students complete as many Create levels as they can.",
        "progression_name": "Create",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Facilitating Create Levels:** Create levels are designed as extensions to the concepts and skills students learn throughout a lesson. Create levels tend to focus on more open-ended tasks for students to complete, or opportunities to combine several skills from previous lessons together into one program.\n\nCreate levels do **not** need to be completed for students to meet the core objectives of a lesson. Instead, every task in a create level is meant to supplement and enrich the learning objectives of a lesson, but are not required for future lessons. Students can still demonstrate mastery of the objectives of a lesson without completing any of the create levels."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "537c8096-6139-4dac-a8b1-24f9561c0499",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78713aad-784a-4465-9f6b-9b434172ce5c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "48516a7e-528e-4451-a0c0-d60b7a82a990",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What's an example of how you used computational thinking in one of the levels today?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should refer back to the Practice levels they completed and the strategies highlighted in each level. By sharing out, students get to hear about choice levels they may have skipped and get new ideas for how computational thinking is tied to building songs with code. Consider having students complete this discussion using the speed pair protocol or another strategy where students can hear many different perspectives quickly"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "48516a7e-528e-4451-a0c0-d60b7a82a990",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d746e2a8-0e99-40ca-b593-0cf69a840100"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f77909ac-a8a5-414a-9e0a-9f2b5c52ea8b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After class has ended, use the Teacher Dashboard to review how much progress students made and how well they did on the Assessment level. Some things to notice might be:\n- Did most students make it to the Assessment level, or are there still a lot of empty progress bubbles?\n- Did students make it to the Assessment level, but did not complete it (ie: green outlines with white circles)?\n- Did students finish the Assessment level and continue to the create levels?\n\nBased on these observations, you can adapt the warm up tomorrow to best meet the needs of the class.",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment Level"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f77909ac-a8a5-414a-9e0a-9f2b5c52ea8b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f909d176-20f6-4d55-9b51-2208eb44f82e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44137ed0-7ef3-42fb-871f-6aac9a7e63f8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before teaching today's lesson, be sure to use the Teacher Dashboard to assess how students did to make a decision for how to start today's lesson. The Warm-Up for this lesson is adaptable based on how well students did with the Assessment level from the previous lesson. ",
        "name": "Reviewing the Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44137ed0-7ef3-42fb-871f-6aac9a7e63f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c2b103a7-c7d0-4077-ae58-31d6af813afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2c8a198-bf59-42af-a69c-b825fb7ee5b9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Start class based on how students performed on yesterday’s Assessment level:\n\n**If many students struggled or didn’t reach the Assessment:** \n- **Whole-Class Reteach** - Walk through a Practice level together, then have students retry the Assessment or move to a Create level.\n\n**If a few students struggled:**\n- **Targeted Support**- Have the class revisit a Create level while you work with students who need extra help.\n\n**If most students did well:**\n- **Move Forward**-  Begin today’s lesson right away to give students more time for practice and deeper exploration.",
        "name": "Differentiated Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2c8a198-bf59-42af-a69c-b825fb7ee5b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2de0a1be-520e-441f-a48c-260c5f647a7a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c64f51e2-1e4b-4681-a09b-b85f574be728",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Set students up for successful Pair Programming by clearly explaining roles, expectations, and when to switch. You can also show [this video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7d_JtyCq1A) to model what it looks like.\n\n**Say:** Today you’ll be working in pairs using Pair Programming. One of you will be the Driver, the person who controls the keyboard and mouse. The other will be the Navigator, who reads the instructions, checks for bugs, and helps think through the steps. Both roles are important, and both of you are responsible for the solution.\nYou must switch roles after each level. This is how both of you learn and stay involved.",
        "name": "Pair Programming"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c64f51e2-1e4b-4681-a09b-b85f574be728",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2de0a1be-520e-441f-a48c-260c5f647a7a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "85c3bd50-7b70-4fde-beff-1b4663ca3729",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work through the levels in class. Students can use their pair programming partners for support, along with the callout icons in instructions and the example music players.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they complete levels. Most of class is spent within levels, providing lots of opportunity to check-in individually with students as needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Prompts to Build Abstraction:** Abstraction is all about focusing on what matters and ignoring what doesn't.  In Music Lab, abstraction shows up when students reduce complexity in their songs, like grouping individual blocks to focus on structure like verses and choruses, or giving meaningful names to functions and sections. Use these questions to help students identify what’s essential in their song or code:\n\n* What’s the main goal of this section of your code?\n* Are there any parts you could group together?\n* If someone new read your code, would they know what it does, or could you simplify it?\n\nThese tips come from our Self-Paced Professional Learning module - [click here to see additional tips and learn more about Abstraction](studio.code.org/s/self-paced-pl-teaching-computer-science-discoveries-music-lab/lessons/4/levels/12)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "85c3bd50-7b70-4fde-beff-1b4663ca3729",
        "lesson_activity.key": "88135275-ed13-4b53-8e83-be9091de2536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8df79fec-5148-4275-aa65-aca4b79a7423",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Abstraction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8df79fec-5148-4275-aa65-aca4b79a7423",
        "lesson_activity.key": "88135275-ed13-4b53-8e83-be9091de2536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00d8f919-dade-45cf-b6d1-55ef5c0817fb",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate & Support:** As students work, check in by asking clarifying or reflective questions like, *What part of your song does this function represent?* or *Could you reuse this function somewhere else in your song?* Encourage thinking about repetition and reusability.",
        "progression_name": "Reusing Functions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00d8f919-dade-45cf-b6d1-55ef5c0817fb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "88135275-ed13-4b53-8e83-be9091de2536"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1121adc-6e10-4cdd-88b6-0709952fa388",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Check-In",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "**Formative Assessment:** Check-in levels are strategically placed in the middle of the lesson so you can check-in on how students are doing while they are still in the room with you and you can adjust instruction if needed. For example:\n- If you notice most students are able to complete the check-in with no assistance, the class can continue to the remaining problems\n- If most of the class is struggling with the check-in, consider regrouping as a class and completing the Investigate levels together or completing the check-in as a class\n- If a few students are struggling, consider working individually with those students to ensure they can be successful in later levels.\n- Use the tips and guiding questions on the [Functions Cheat Sheet.](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1PFQdLhk1Yi4HdzBmI17N31GtybQcm2Nm/view)"
          }
        ]
      },
